-- Diageo, Heritage Oil, Polar, Toledo: U.K., Irish Equity Preview
-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t   a n d   S a r a h   J o n e s
-- 2010-12-10T07:47:45Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-09/african-minerals-toledo-polar-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index  rose 13.43, or 0.2 percent, to
5,807.96. The  FTSE All-Share Index  advanced 0.3 percent, while
Ireland’s  ISEQ Index  rose 1 percent.  African Minerals Ltd.  (AMI LN): The diamond and metal
explorer’s Chief Financial Officer Miguel Perry said discussions
on a proposed $1.5 billion investment by Shandong Iron & Steel
Group Co. are going “very well” after a delay earlier this
year in reaching an accord. The stock was unchanged at 405
pence.  Allied Irish Banks Plc  (ALBK ID): The restructuring plan
for the lender to be negotiated with European Union competition
authorities will “place clear conditionality on remuneration to
executives,” European Commission President Jose Barroso said at
a press conference in Brussels. The shares were unchanged at 50
euro cents.  Diageo Plc  (DGE LN): The spirits maker is in early
discussions to buy Mey Icki Sanayi Ltd. that would value the
Turkish company at between $2 billion and $2.5 billion, the Wall
Street Journal reported, citing people familiar with the matter.
The shares rose 0.4 percent to 1,163 pence.  Heritage Oil Plc  (HOIL LN): Malaysia’s Petroliam Nasional
Bhd, known as Petronas, may make a 1.71 billion pounds ($2.7
billion) cash bid for U.K.-based company, the Daily Mail
reported, without saying where it obtained the information. The
shares gained 4.1 percent to 427 pence.  Polar Capital Holdings Plc  (POLR LN): The U.K. money
manager founded in 2001 said assets under management rose more
than 20 percent to $3.1 billion in the six months ending Sept.
30, compared to the previous half. The shares were unchanged at
141 pence.  Rolls-Royce Group Plc  (RR/ LN): The company may face costs
of $500 million over the next few years to redesign key parts of
its Trent 900 engine and pay compensation to customers after the
engine exploded on a Qantas Airways Ltd. Airbus A380 flight on
Nov. 4, the Financial Times reported, citing aviation experts.
The shares lost 1.5 percent to 642 pence.  Toledo Mining Corp.  (TMC LN): The developer of nickel mines
in the Phillipines said in a statement it received a preliminary
approach that may or may not lead to an offer for the company.
The shares surged 14 percent to 27.25 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
